Unwraps this `Pin<Ptr>`, returning the underlying pointer.

Doing this operation safely requires that the data pointed at by this pinning pointer implements [`Unpin`](../marker/trait.Unpin.html "trait std::marker::Unpin") so that we can ignore the pinning invariants when unwrapping it.

##### [¬ß](#examples-1)Examples

```
use std::pin::Pin;

let mut val: u8 = 5;
let pinned: Pin<&mut u8> = Pin::new(&mut val);

// Unwrap the pin to get the underlying mutable reference to the value. We can do
// this because `val` doesn't care about being moved, so the `Pin` was just
// a "facade" anyway.
let r = Pin::into_inner(pinned);
assert_eq!(*r, 5);
```

