Assigns a new value to the memory location pointed to by the `Pin<Ptr>`.

This overwrites pinned data, but that is okay: the original pinned value‚Äôs destructor gets run before being overwritten and the new value is also a valid value of the same type, so no pinning invariant is violated. See [the `pin` module documentation](about:blank/index.html#subtle-details-and-the-drop-guarantee "mod std::pin") for more information on how this upholds the pinning invariants.

##### [¬ß](#example-1)Example

```
use std::pin::Pin;

let mut val: u8 = 5;
let mut pinned: Pin<&mut u8> = Pin::new(&mut val);
println!("{}", pinned); // 5
pinned.set(10);
println!("{}", pinned); // 10
```

